{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616885"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:08:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:08:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16442"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16442"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.03,0.07,0,0.67]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9133"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65489"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9133"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16442"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50928"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5113"},{"type":"tags","id":"10025"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21696"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21798"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65489"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EVitamin D plays a crucial role in calcium homeostasis and bone metabolism. The vitamin D produced in the skin or obtained through diet must undergo several modifications before becoming biologically active.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the metabolic activation pathway of vitamin D?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Initial hydroxylation in kidneys followed by liver activation","Single-step activation in the liver only","Simultaneous hydroxylation in liver and kidneys","Direct activation in bone tissue","Initial hydroxylation in liver followed by kidney activation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct metabolic pathway involves \u003Cstrong\u003Einitial hydroxylation in liver followed by kidney activation\u003C/strong\u003E. Vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol) is first converted to 25-hydroxyvitamin D in the liver by vitamin D 25-hydroxylase. This intermediate form then undergoes further hydroxylation in the kidneys by 1-alpha-hydroxylase to produce the active form, 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D. This two-step hydroxylation process allows tight regulation of active vitamin D levels, with the kidney step being particularly important as it responds to calcium and parathyroid hormone levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitial hydroxylation in kidneys followed by liver activation\u003C/strong\u003E incorrectly reverses the order of the activation process. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle-step activation in the liver only\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because vitamin D requires two separate hydroxylation steps. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimultaneous hydroxylation in liver and kidneys\u003C/strong\u003E does not accurately describe the sequential nature of the vitamin D activation process. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect activation in bone tissue\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; bone tissue is a target organ for vitamin D but does not participate in its activation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol) is converted to 25-hydroxyvitamin D in the liver by vitamin D 25-hydroxylase.","The active form of vitamin D (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D) is produced in the kidneys by 1-alpha-hydroxylase.","Vitamin D metabolism requires sequential hydroxylation steps in both the liver and kidneys."],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50928"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16442"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50928"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T14:23:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T16:44:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9133"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65489"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":